    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-21T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-21T12:00:00-05:00" n="719"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/12452</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-21T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 21, 1917, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received May 21, 5.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6260. Department’s 4832, May 14.<note n="1" xml:id="d719fn1">Not printed.</note>
                    Foreign Office informs me to-day that, <hi rend="italic">re</hi> goods in
                    Rotterdam, it has accumulating evidence showing goods are still being ordered
                    into Holland from Germany by American merchants with object of shipping after
                    the war, this evidence coming from intercepted letter in case of Swiss Clock
                    Company of New York, some of the goods referred to in it being still in Germany
                    and have not been paid for.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>The United States Government would doubtless refuse to support any
                        application for shipment of such goods but your excellency will see from
                        this instance that if any further facilities are to be granted for shipment
                        of enemy’s goods from Rotterdam to America the utmost care will have to be
                        exercised to insure that only <hi rend="italic">bona fide</hi> applications
                        are granted and that orders of this kind will receive no consideration.</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
